from sklearn.manifold import MDS

mds = MDS(normalized_stress='auto')
scaled_df = mds.fit_transform(pois_df)

CO1 = scaled_df[:,0]
CO2 = scaled_df[:,1]

plt.scatter(CO1,CO2,marker=1)
plt.title("MDS")
plt.xlabel("Coordinate 1")
plt.ylabel("Coordinate 2")
plt.show()

The data is grouped in an orderly fashion, no subgroups stand out. It is very uniform and therefore the data seems truly random.

from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

mms = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0,1))
stc = StandardScaler()
# now we normalize the data as the absorption of ir spectral light can differ greatly
# there are also some values below zero which is ofcourse not possible
#normalize the data
salv_data = salv_df.iloc[:,1:]
salv_data = salv_data.subtract(salv_data.mean(axis=1), axis=0)
salv_data.iloc[:,:] = mms.fit_transform(salv_data)# every value minimum of 0 maximum of 1
salv_data.iloc[:,:] = stc.fit_transform(salv_data)# every value average of 0 and stdev of 1

Now that we have normalized, and created this wonderfull plot lets first perform PCA on the data followed by LDA (because we have two distinct groups).

In [ ]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

pca = PCA()

# first lets perform a scree plot
pca.fit(salv_df.iloc[:,1:])
pc_ratios = pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:30]
pc_x_range = np.linspace(1,30,30)
plt.scatter(x=pc_x_range, y=pc_ratios*100)
plt.xlabel("n_component")
plt.ylabel("explained variance (%)")
plt.title("PCA scree plot")
plt.show()

So a huge portion of the variance can be explained in the first principle component.

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.patches as mpatches

colors = salv_df['ID'].values
color_dict = {'P':'pink','N':'cyan'}

PC1 = pca.fit_transform(salv_df.iloc[:,1:])[:,0]
PC2 = pca.fit_transform(salv_df.iloc[:,1:])[:,1]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 9))
for c,p1,p2 in zip(colors,PC1,PC2):
    col = color_dict[c[0]]
    ax.scatter(p1, p2, color=col)
pink_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='pink', label='Positive')
cyan_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='cyan', label='Negative')

ax.set_xlabel(f'PC1({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0]*100:.3}%)', fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel(f'PC2({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[1]*100:.3}%)', fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('PCA', fontsize=20)
ax.legend(handles=[pink_patch,cyan_patch])

plt.show()

Shown in the PCA is no clear seperation between the groups. But as we already know the groups we may use LDA to maximize the difference.

In [ ]:
#Lets try the LDA
from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import LinearDiscriminantAnalysis as LDA

salv_df.columns = salv_df.columns.astype(str)

dict_val = {'P':1,'N':0}

salv_df["group"] = [dict_val[val[0]] for val in salv_df["ID"].values]

y = salv_df["group"]

lda = LDA(n_components=1)
LD = lda.fit_transform(salv_df.iloc[:,1:], y)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 9))
for c,l1 in zip(colors,LD):
    col = color_dict[c[0]]
    ax.scatter(l1, y=dict_val[c[0]] , color=col)
plt.yticks([-1,0,1,2])
pink_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='pink', label='Positive')
cyan_patch = mpatches.Patch(color='cyan', label='Negative')
ax.set_xlabel('LD', fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel('Positive (1), Negative (0)', fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('Linear discriminant', fontsize=20)
ax.legend(handles=[pink_patch,cyan_patch])
plt.show()

The difference between the groups are maximized, and it becomes clear that there in fact is a difference.
